{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5616ca8e-5748-42e0-8790-bf404cc2dd97","content":"Here's what breaks in each case and the fixes:\n\n---\n\n**1. `SpanHelper.cs` — Stricter `scoped` ref-safety**\n\nC# 15 tightens span lifetime analysis. `Span<int> items = [x * 2]` inside the loop targets `Span<T>` via a collection expression, which may use implicit `stackalloc`. That memory's lifetime is the loop iteration. Assigning it to `results` (declared outside the loop) widens the reference lifetime — now a compile error.\n\n**Fix:** Accumulate into a `List<int>` instead:\n\n```csharp\npublic static int[] ProcessItems(int[] source)\n{\n    var results = new List<int>();\n    foreach (var x in source)\n        results.Add(x * 2);\n    return results.ToArray();\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. `Metadata.cs` — `this` disallowed in `nameof` in attribute arguments**\n\nC# 15 enforces that `this` is unavailable in attribute argument context (a static/compile-time context). Even though `nameof` doesn't evaluate its operand, the `this` keyword is no longer permitted there. C# 14 was permissive about this; C# 15 closes the gap.\n\n**Fix:** Drop the `this` qualifier:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Obsolete(nameof(Endpoint))]\nvoid LegacyConnect() { }\n```\n\n---\n\n**3. `Pipeline.cs` — `with` contextual keyword expanded into collection expressions**\n\nC# 15 extends `with`'s contextual keyword status. Inside a collection expression `[...]`, the parser now interprets `with(x, y)` as the beginning of a `with` expression (non-destructive mutation), not a method invocation. This produces a parse error.\n\n**Fix:** Escape the identifier or rename:\n\n```csharp\n// Option A: verbatim identifier\nobject @with(object a, object b) => (a, b);\nobject[] items = [@with(x, y), z];\n\n// Option B: rename\nobject Combine(object a, object b) => (a, b);\nobject[] items = [Combine(x, y), z];\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"61ecf9fd-d722-4587-ad3c-01dded358294","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"T