hanges to how `nameof` works with instance members in attributes. \n\nHmm, but actually the real issue might be simpler: `Endpoint` is a field (not a property), and `nameof(this.Endpoint)` - in C# 14, this might have worked in attribute contexts as a special case of `nameof`, but in C# 15, the rules might have been tightened.\n\nI'm not entirely sure about the exact C# 15 changes here, but one plausible explanation is that C# 15 tightened the rules so `nameof` in attributes no longer allows `this` qualification, requiring just `nameof(Endpoint)` instead. As for the `with` method name issue in `Pipeline.cs`, that's clearer - `with` is a contextual keyword used for record copying expressions since C# 9, and while it can normally be used as an identifier, the problem arises when it appears in a collection expression like `[with(x, y), z]` where the parser gets confused about whether it's a keyword or a method call. I'm wondering if C# 14 had a permissive bug or intentional relaxation that allowed `nameof(this.Endpoint)` in attribute contexts, and C# 15 tightened this restriction since `this` shouldn't be available in that static-like scope anyway.\n\nFor the `with` keyword, it might be expanding its contextual keyword status in C# 15 to cover more syntactic positions like collection expressions, so renaming the method or using an escaped identifier would fix it.\n\nLet me reconsider the version mapping here—C# 12 corresponds to .NET 8, C# 13 to .NET 9, and C# 14 to .NET 10, so C# 15 would align with .NET 11.\n\nSince .NET 11 and C# 15 are future versions that may not be fully specified yet, I'm reasoning about plausible breaking changes based on the language's trajectory. The user has shown code that worked in C# 14 but breaks now, so I should analyze what realistic language evolution could cause these specific failures.\n\nThe first issue involves `scoped Span` reassignment—C# 15 likely tightened ref-safety rules so you can't assign a span with a narrower lifetime (created in a loop) to one with a broader lifetime (method-scoped), even when both are scoped. The fix would be using a `List<int>` or pre-allocated array instead. The second issue is with `nameof(this.Endpoint)` in attribute arguments—C# 15 probably restricted using `this` in `nameof` within attributes since they're evaluated at compile time.\n\nFor the third issue, `with` is becoming a contextual keyword in C# 15, so inside collection expressions it gets parsed as the start of a `with` expression rather than a method call. The fix is either escaping it as `@with` or renaming the method.\n\nI should double-check whether these are actual C# 15 changes or just hypothetical ones, especially given we're in April 2026 now. preview would likely be starting around this time:\n\n1. The `scoped` span safety one - this aligns with the ongoing work in the C# team to tighten ref safety. There have been proposals to close loopholes where stack-allocated spans could be assigned to variables with wider scopes.\n\n2. The `nameof(this.X)` in attributes - I need to be careful here. `nameof` can reference instance members from static contexts in recent C# versions, but `this` is special since it's a keyword, not just a name lookup. So `nameof(Endpoint)` would work in an attribute, but `nameof(this.Endpoint)` shouldn't be allowed.\n\n3. For the `with` method name - collection expressions were introduced in C# 12, and having `with` as a keyword conflict inside them seems like a plausible breaking change.\n\nLet me finalize my analysis and write clear explanations for these, keeping in mind we're in April 2026 where some C# 15 previews might already be circulating. For the second issue, C# 15 disallows `this` inside `nameof` expressions used in attributes since `this` isn't available in that compile-time context, whereas C# 14 was more lenient. The fix is straightforward—just remove the `this` qualifier and reference the member directly.\n\nThe third issue involves a parsing conflict where